questiontext.text:
The parabola with equation \(y={@polyform@}\), where \(k\neq0\) is a constant, is shown in the diagram below.

[[jsxgraph width='250px' height='150px']] /* boundingbox:[left, top, right, bottom] */ JXG.Options.axis.ticks.majorHeight = 10; JXG.Options.axis.ticks.insertTicks = false; JXG.Options.axis.ticks.ticksDistance = 200; JXG.Options.text.fontSize = 16; var board = JXG.JSXGraph.initBoard(divid, {boundingbox: [-1,5,5,-1], axis: true, showCopyright: false, showNavigation:false}); var f = board.jc.snippet('-x*(x-4)', true, 'x', true); var plot = board.create('functiongraph', [f,-1,5],{strokeColor:'#003399',strokeWidth:2}); var i1 = board.create('integral', [[0,4], plot], {fillColor:'#003399',fillOpacity:0.15}); i1.curveLeft.setAttribute({visible:false}); i1.curveRight.setAttribute({visible:false}); i1.label.setAttribute({visible:false}); [[/jsxgraph]]

Given that the shaded area is {@A@} square units, find the value of \(k\).

\(k=\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]

generalfeedback.text:
We first need to find the roots of the parabola. Factorising gives

\[ {@polyform@}={@factor(polyform)@} \]

so the roots are at {@x=0@} and {@x=r1@}.

This means the shaded area is given by

\[ \begin{align*} \int_0^{@r1@} \left({@polyform@}\right)\,dx &= \left[{@integrate(polyform,x)@}\right]_0^{@r1@} \\ &= {@integrate(polyform,x,0,r1)@}. \end{align*} \]

We are given that this has the value {@A@}. So we have

\[ \begin{align*} {@integrate(polyform,x,0,r1)@} &= {@A@}  \\  k &= {@kval@} \end{align*} \]
